\chapter{Measures of Central Tendency}
\label{chap:ch3}

\section{Objective}

By the end of this material, you will be able to
\begin{itemize}
\item Explain the purposes of measures of central tendency and interpret the 
information they provide.
\item Calculate, explain and compare modes, medians and means.
\item Understand other measures of central tendency
\item Be able to select appropriate measure of central tendency according to the 
level of measurement and characteristics of the distribution.
\end{itemize}

\section{Three Common Measures}

The central tendency is a measure of where most of the data is located.

\begin{itemize}
\item mean
\item median
\item mode
\end{itemize}

\section{Average or Mean}

The \emph{mean} is the arithmetic center of a distribution and is the most commonly utilized measure.  It reports the average score of a distribution.

The strength and weakness of the mean.

\begin{itemize}
\item Strength -- All data from a variable are used to compute the mean.
\item Weakness -- The mean is affected by extreme values (\emph{outliers}).
\end{itemize}

