\section{Median}

The \emph{median} is the value of the middle observation when the data is sorted.

\begin{itemize}
\item If there is an odd number of data values, then to find the center value, simply order the values and remove them from the beginning and end to find the center, e.g., 

% Requires the booktabs if the memoir class is not being used
\begin{table}[htbp]
   \centering
   %\topcaption{Table captions are better up top} % requires the topcapt package
   \begin{tabular}{@{} lllll @{}} % Column formatting, @{} suppresses leading/trailing space
       2 & 4 & 4 & 6  & 9 \\
   \end{tabular}
   % \caption{Remember, \emph{never} use vertical lines in tables.}
   \label{tab:tab8}
\end{table}

\item median = 4

\item If there is an even number of data values, then to find the center two values and average them,  e.g., 

% Requires the booktabs if the memoir class is not being used
\begin{table}[htbp]
   \centering
   %\topcaption{Table captions are better up top} % requires the topcapt package
   \begin{tabular}{@{} llllll @{}} % Column formatting, @{} suppresses leading/trailing space
       2 & 4 & 4 & 5 & 6  & 9 \\
   \end{tabular}
   % \caption{Remember, \emph{never} use vertical lines in tables.}
   \label{tab:tab9}
\end{table}

\item $median = \frac{4 + 5}{2} = 4.5 $

\end{itemize}

The {\bf{median}} is the center score of the distribution.  Half of the values are below the median and half are above the median in the distribution. 

\begin{itemize}
\item Strength:  It is RESISTANT to extreme value (\emph{outliers}).
\item Weakness: Not all data from a variable is used to compute the median. 
\end{itemize}

\section{Mode}

The {\bf{mode}} is the most frequently occurring observation of this variable.

\begin{itemize}
\item For example:

% Requires the booktabs if the memoir class is not being used
\begin{table}[htbp]
   \centering
   %\topcaption{Table captions are better up top} % requires the topcapt package
   \begin{tabular}{@{} lllll @{}} % Column formatting, @{} suppresses leading/trailing space
       2 & 4 & 4 & 6  & 9 \\
   \end{tabular}
   % \caption{Remember, \emph{never} use vertical lines in tables.}
   \label{tab:tab8}
\end{table}

The most frequently occurring value is 4, since there are two of them, so the {\bf{mode}} is 4.

\item Strength:  It is RESISTANT to extreme values (\emph{outliers}).
\item Weakness: NOT all data from a variable is used to compute the {\bf{mode}}.
\end{itemize}

